Articles.Content: It goes to figure that if you change the aerodynamics, and therefore, the delta-v calculations, that Engineer would barf all over your screen.
I get this behavior occasionally as well. Sometimes I have to quicksave, quit KSP completely, then reload and it comes back fine.

The Surface display causes the Engineer to freak out when in atmosphere because FAR overrides the default KSP atmosphere values and uses ones it calculates itself. However, Engineer does not know this and tries to use the default values that are now wrong.

Engineer screws up and you get the short grey window. You can workaround this by leaving the atmosphere or closing the surface display part of the engineer while your ship is in atmosphere.

I have a question: does it correctly calculate Delta-V when you use pipes between stages? I load 1440 fuel and Mainsail on the central stage, then 4x1440 and Skipper engines on the sides, with sequential pipes. And it seems I have more delta-V than flight engineer predicts.

I might load a bit more than needed for LKO (usually I make about 4900 m/s). Last time I had about 700 m/s of delta-V left in the central Mainsail stage, which was almost enough for translunar injection.

A couple of ideas: when you make an apollo-style missions, it's impossible to calculate correctly the command/service module delta-v, because first it's used together with lunar module, but the rest of Delta-V is used for this stage alone. And same problem arises when you have two ships docked: you don't know the delta-V before you actually undock or decouple a stage (if I want to deorbit it later), which makes you leave too much fuel in the tanks. If this could be resolved, users could spend much less fuel and avoid unnecessarily huge rockets.

Update

...it's impossible to calculate correctly the command/service module delta-v, because first it's used together with lunar module...

You can fix this in the VAB (though not flight) with SelectRoot - I often use it to take apart multiple craft (lander, CSM, comms sat etc) inside one launcher:

Set the sub-craft's control part as root. Then, detach everything else and voila - that sub-craft's stats show since it's the final stage.

Combine this with the Subassembly manager (can't find the link) and you've got really modular craft with stats on each, making repetitive and custom launches very easy.

I think I may have found a bug...

When I use the engineer in combination with any animated part from the SpaceTech packs (Landing Platform and Landing Program in particular), the engineering GUI fails to update after first displaying a figure for dV. This bug does NOT apply to the fuel tanks or engines being used in conjunction with other parts, though, so I think it may be tied to the animated parts. In addition, it seems to have trouble with the decoupler heatshields seemingly at random.

I'm not sure if it's an issue with my computer running up against RAM limits, a flaw with the particular designs I'm using, or if it's an across-the-board issue that can be repeated. Can anyone confirm these issues?

There appears to be a bug where Engineer does not recognize radially-attached engines on a part that has ModuleDecouple. The specific case I have is to attach engines radially to the SDHI Service Module:

http://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/threads/48357-WIP-Sum-Dum-Heavy-Industries-Service-Module-System-(Stockalike)

KER does not show any dV from radial engines attached to the SM, but MechJeb does. If I comment out the decoupler module, KER recognizes the engines.

Some parts magically change their mass when they leave the hangar, such as landing gear shows up as .5 tons per gear, but is completely weightless in the launchpad/runway. This is why you balance your aircraft and look at TWR and dV before you put the gear on. Other things may be launch clamps, and possibly other landing gear or ladders. I have no idea what else has this "feature".

Have you got it calculating with the atmospheric adjustment inside the VAB? Engineer defaults to using vacuum Isp which will result in a much higher deltaV readout, but this can be toggled using the button at the top. When you go to launch, it will use actual Isp based on the current atmospheric properties.
I want Kerbal Engineer to have a feature that shows delta-v based only on RCS monopropellant and thrusters.
